{{more footnotes|date</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><bold>Andocides</bold><space/>(<template><target>IPAc-en</target><arg>ˌ</arg><arg>æ</arg><arg>n</arg><arg>d</arg><arg>oʊ</arg><arg>ˈ</arg><arg>s</arg><arg>aɪ</arg><arg>d</arg><arg>iː</arg><arg>z</arg></template>;<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.infoplease.com/encyclopedia/people/andocides.html'>&quot;Andocides&quot;</link>.<space/><link><target>Columbia Encyclopedia</target><part>''The Columbia Electronic Encyclopedia''</part></link>, 6th ed., Columbia University Press, 2012.</extension><space/><template><target>lang-grc-gre</target><arg>Ἀνδοκίδης</arg></template>,<space/><italics>Andokides</italics>; c. 440 c. 390 BC) was a<space/><link><target>logographer (legal)</target><part>logographer</part></link><space/>(speech writer) in Ancient Greece. He was one of the ten<space/><link><target>Attic orators</target></link><space/>included in the &quot;Alexandrian Canon&quot; compiled by<space/><link><target>Aristophanes of Byzantium</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Aristarchus of Samothrace</target></link><space/>in the third century BC.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Life</heading><paragraph>He was implicated during the<space/><link><target>Peloponnesian War</target></link><space/>in the mutilation of the<space/><link><target>Herms</target></link><space/>on the eve of the departure of the<space/><link><target>Sicilian expedition</target><part>Athenian expedition</part></link><space/>against<space/><link><target>Sicily</target></link><space/>in 415 BC. Although he saved his life by turning informer, he was condemned to partial loss of civil rights and forced to leave Athens. He engaged in commercial pursuits, and returned to<space/><link><target>Classical Athens</target><part>Athens</part></link><space/>under the general amnesty that followed the restoration of the democracy (403 BC), and filled some important offices. In 391 BC he was one of the ambassadors sent to<space/><link><target>Sparta</target></link><space/>to discuss peace terms, but the negotiations failed.<space/><link><target>oligarchy</target><part>Oligarch</part><trail>ical</trail></link><space/>in his sympathies, he offended his own party and was distrusted by the democrats.<template><target>sfn</target><arg>Chisholm</arg><arg>1911</arg></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>List of extant speeches</heading><list type='numbered'><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Andoc.+1+1'>On the Mysteries</link><space/>(<template><target>lang</target><arg>grc</arg><arg>Περὶ τῶν μυστηρίων</arg></template><space/>&quot;<italics>De Mysteriis</italics>&quot;). Andocides' defense against the charge of impiety in attending the<space/><link><target>Eleusinian Mysteries</target></link>.</listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Andoc.+2+1'>On His Return</link><space/>(<template><target>lang</target><arg>grc</arg><arg>Περὶ τῆς ἑαυτοῦ καθόδου</arg></template><space/>&quot;<italics>De Reditu</italics>&quot;). Andocides' plea for his return and removal of civil disabilities.</listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Andoc.+3+1'>On the Peace with Sparta</link><space/>(<template><target>lang</target><arg>grc</arg><arg>Περὶ τῆς πρὸς Λακεδαιμονίους εἰρήνης</arg></template><space/>&quot;<italics>De Pace</italics>&quot;). An argument for peace with Sparta.</listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?lookup=Andoc.+4+1'>Against Alcibiades</link><space/>(<template><target>lang</target><arg>grc</arg><arg>Κατὰ Ἀλκιβιάδου</arg></template><space/>&quot;<italics>Contra<space/><link><target>Alcibiades</target><part>Alcibiadem</part></link></italics>&quot;).<space/><italics>Generally considered spurious.</italics></listitem></list><heading level='2'>Notes</heading><paragraph><template><target>reflist</target></template></paragraph><list type='def'><listitem><defkey>Attribution</defkey></listitem></list><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>EB1911</target><arg name="wstitle">Andocides</arg><arg name="volume">1</arg></template></listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem>Andocides. (<link type='external' href='http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0018'>Speeches</link><space/>at the Perseus Project.)</listitem></list><heading level='2'>External links</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>Wikisourcelang-inline</target><arg>el</arg><arg>Ανδοκίδης</arg><arg>Andocides</arg></template></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://demonax.info/doku.php?id=text:andocides_orations'>Andocides Orations</link></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>Attic orators</target></template><template><target>Ancient Athenian statesmen</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Authority control</target></template></paragraph><paragraph><link><target>Category:440 BC</target></link><link><target>Category:390 BC</target></link><link><target>Category:Attic orators</target></link><link><target>Category:5th-century BC Greek people</target></link><link><target>Category:4th-century BC Greek people</target></link><link><target>Category:Ancient Greeks accused of sacrilege</target></link><link><target>Category:People of the Peloponnesian War</target></link><link><target>Category:440s BC births</target></link><link><target>Category:390s BC deaths</target></link></paragraph></article>